# **A/B Test Analysis of Marketing Campaigns**

[**Scenario**](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/chebotinaa/fast-food-marketing-campaign-ab-test)  
A fast-food chain plans to add a new item to its menu. However, they are still undecided between three possible marketing campaigns for promoting the new product. In order to determine which promotion has the greatest effect on sales, the new item is introduced at locations in several randomly selected markets. A different promotion is used at each location, and the weekly sales of the new item are recorded for the first four weeks.

# **Goal of the Test**

# The goal of this analysis is to evaluate the performance of three marketing campaigns based on weekly sales data and determine which campaign performed the best.

For analysis of A/B test results we will use a confidence level of 99% (as suggested in the task description).

**Target Metric**

The target metric is *Sales in Thousands* since we wanna identify the campaign that will generate the biggest sales for the new fast-food item.   
I calculated not weekly but monthly sales (=sum(sales\_in\_thousands) by location). 

**Hypothesis formulation**

*Null hypothesis*: there is no significant difference in the performance of 3 marketing campaigns

*Alternative hypothesis*: there is a significant difference in the performance of 3 marketing campaigns (or at least two of them). 

**Calculations**

Here is the summary statistics for all 3 campaigns (see the Query in the appendix). 

| Promotion | mean\_sales | st\_dev | n\_count |
| ----- | :---: | :---: | :---: |
| Promotion 1 | 232.3960465 | 64.11289125 | 43 |
| Promotion 2 | 189.3176596 | 57.98838944 | 47 |
| Promotion 3 | 221.4578723 | 65.53546268 | 47 |

We see that Promotion1 has the highest mean sales which let us assume that Promotion1 performed the best and we can reject the H0. In order to do so we need to check for statistical significance.

I’ll conduct several tests, comparing campaigns against one another. Since such pairwise comparisons suffer from the multiple testing problem\* it is suggested to use the confidence level of 99% (corresponding to alpha of 0.01). 

The t-tests were done on [google sheets](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1OV-Z5a200De5sNDQUPi2hGNgP7KoQlw9ENjaaE94oRo/edit?gid=1386133591#gid=1386133591) (using TTEST function). Here are the calculated p-values:

| t-test promo1 vs promo2 |  |  |
| ----- | :---- | :---- |
| 0.001202567461 | \<0.01 | there is a significant difference |
|  |  |  |
| **t-test promo1 vs promo3** |  |  |
| 0.4263564328 | \>0.01 | there is no significant difference |
|  |  |  |
| **t-test promo2 vs promo3** |  |  |
| 0.01353146115 | \>0.01 | there is no significant difference |

Given that our confidence level was 99% (corresponding to alpha of 0.01) and the p-value Promo1 vs Promo2 approximately 0.0012, the difference between the variants is statistically significant (while we see no significant difference P1 vs P3 and P2 vs P3).

The low p-value indicates that we would be very unlikely to get such a difference or larger by chance alone.

\*if we run a lot of tests, there’s an increased chance of getting a type I error (false positive)

## **Campaigns 1 vs 2**

The difference between campaigns 1 and 2 is statistically significant. Campaign 1 performs better than campaign 2 with a difference of means of 43 thousand dollars. In other words, over the period of the test, campaign 1 generated an estimated 43 thousand dollars more than campaign 2\.

![][image1]

## **Campaigns 2 vs 3**

The difference between campaigns 2 and 3 is not statistically significant. Given the alpha level I set before this analysis, the p-value of 0.0136 is too high. To establish statistical significance, the test should be run for longer or in more locations.

![][image2]

## **Campaigns 1 vs 3**

Likewise, the difference between campaigns 1 and 3 is not statistically significant.

![][image3]

# **Decision & recommendations**

The promotion 1 performed the best during the 4-weeks test period based on the mean sales.

But since we see no significant difference Promo1 vs Promo3 it’s recommended either continue with Promo1 or (in case of budget availability) prolong the test period in order to confirm/not confirm whether Promo3 performs similar to Promo1 (bigger sample size may give us better understanding). 

Promo2 should be discontinued. 

*Further recommendations*:

- Prolong the test in order to increase the sample size hence have more reliable results  
- Conduct the analysis by market\_size and age\_of\_store   
- Check the sample ratio mismatch 

**Appendix**

1. **Query** 

**`-- Calculate stats for Promotion 1`**  
**`WITH promo_1 AS (`**  
  **`SELECT`**  
    **`location_id,`**  
    **`sum(sales_in_thousands) AS sales`**  
  **`FROM`**  
    **`` `tc-da-1.turing_data_analytics.wa_marketing_campaign` ``**  
  **`WHERE Promotion = 1`**  
  **`GROUP BY location_id`**  
**`),`**  
**`stats_1 AS (`**  
  **`SELECT`**  
    **`AVG(sales) AS mean_sales,`**  
    **`stddev(sales) AS st_dev,`**  
    **`VARIANCE(sales) AS var_sales,`**  
    **`COUNT(location_id) AS n_count`**  
  **`FROM promo_1`**  
**`)`**

**`-- Calculate stats for Promotion 2`**  
**`, promo_2 AS (`**  
  **`SELECT`**  
    **`location_id,`**  
    **`sum(sales_in_thousands) AS sales`**  
  **`FROM`**  
    **`` `tc-da-1.turing_data_analytics.wa_marketing_campaign` ``**  
  **`WHERE Promotion = 2`**  
  **`GROUP BY location_id`**  
**`),`**  
**`stats_2 AS (`**  
  **`SELECT`**  
    **`AVG(sales) AS mean_sales,`**  
    **`stddev(sales) AS st_dev,`**  
    **`VARIANCE(sales) AS var_sales,`**  
    **`COUNT(location_id) AS n_count`**  
  **`FROM promo_2`**  
**`)`**

**`-- Calculate stats for Promotion 3`**  
**`, promo_3 AS (`**  
  **`SELECT`**  
    **`location_id,`**  
    **`sum(sales_in_thousands) AS sales`**  
  **`FROM`**  
    **`` `tc-da-1.turing_data_analytics.wa_marketing_campaign` ``**  
  **`WHERE Promotion = 3`**  
  **`GROUP BY location_id`**  
**`),`**  
**`stats_3 AS (`**  
  **`SELECT`**  
    **`AVG(sales) AS mean_sales,`**  
    **`stddev(sales) AS st_dev,`**  
    **`VARIANCE(sales) AS var_sales,`**  
    **`COUNT(location_id) AS n_count`**  
  **`FROM promo_3`**  
**`)`**

**`-- Combine the results into a single output`**  
**`SELECT`**  
  **`'Promotion 1' AS Promotion, mean_sales, st_dev, var_sales, n_count`**  
**`FROM stats_1`**  
**`UNION ALL`**  
**`SELECT`**  
  **`'Promotion 2' AS Promotion, mean_sales, st_dev, var_sales, n_count`**  
**`FROM stats_2`**  
**`UNION ALL`**  
**`SELECT`**  
  **`'Promotion 3' AS Promotion, mean_sales, st_dev, var_sales, n_count`**  
**`FROM stats_3;`**
